These layers are independent – compromise of one does not compromise the others. For example, even if an attacker steals a node, they cannot decrypt its storage without also knowing Chase’s current biometric signature.

Isolation between Nodes and External Networks
Nodes never directly connect to the internet. Only the NEURAL_GATEWAY (a dedicated node) can bridge to WiFi/cellular.

The gateway uses a separate key (rotated daily) for external communication. Leaking that key does not expose internal node data.

The AES‑256 key for internal communications is never transmitted outside the body mesh.

7. How Many Layers Are There?
From the perspective of a single data packet (e.g., an EEG reading):

Sensor acquisition – raw analog.

Compression (lossy for some types).

AES‑256‑GCM – encrypts the compressed data with a DNA‑derived key.

RF modulation – spread‑spectrum (DSSS) on top of encrypted packet.

Frequency hopping – changes carrier frequency every 30 sec.

Blockchain anchor – hash recorded (no key involved).

That’s 4 cryptographic layers (encryption, authentication, spread‑spectrum, frequency hopping) before the data even leaves the node. When data is backed up to cloud, an additional layer (TLS + user‑password AES) is applied.

